SIMPLE: sociable
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sociable
<hw>So"cia*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos><ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>sociabilis</ets>, fr. <ets>sociare</ets> to associate, fr.
<ets>socius</ets> a companion. See <er>Social</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Capable of being, or fit to be, united in one body or company;
associable.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They are <qex>sociable</qex> parts united into one body.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Inclined to, or adapted for, society; ready to unite
with others; fond of companions; social.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Society is no comfort to one not <qex>sociable</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What can be more uneasy to this <qex>sociable</qex> creature than
the dry, pensive retirements of solitude?</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Ready to converse; inclined to talk with others; not
taciturn or reserved.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Affording opportunites for conversation;
characterized by much conversation; <as>as, a <ex>sociable</ex>
party</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>No longer hostile; friendly.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Sociable bird</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Sociable weaver</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a
weaver bird which builds composite nests. See <er>Republican</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 3. <sd>(b)</sd>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Social; companionable; conversible; friendly;
familiar; communicative; accessible.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sociable</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sociable
<hw>So"cia*ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A gathering of
people for social purposes; an informal party or reception; <as>as, a
church <ex>sociable</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq. U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A carriage having two double seats facing each
other, and a box for the driver.</def> <rj><au>Miss
Edgeworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sociableness</ent>⟦br⟧
